@ben0x539 I've only really used OCaml for hobby coding and have become distracted by Rust more recently. Safe systems programming etc etc.
@ben0x539 I think C# actually deports itself well for a language in it's class, so Nemerle sounds interesting. Also, have you tried F#?
@ben0x539 Again OCaml's got you covered with partial application via named parameters, but it can get a little finicky.
@ben0x539 yeah, the nice thing there is that the partial application doesn't have to be on the last arg
@ben0x539 it's nice to see how much of ML is making it's way into other languages though. Slowly but slowly :-)
@ben0x539 you need partial application to make that kind of pipelining work too.

@ben0x539 yeah, it's really nice in many ways. Sometimes a little more verbose, e.g. 
vals |> List.filter is_even |> List.map string_of_int
@ben0x539 I think there's something to be said for having a small set of methods/funcs with private access that maintain invariants
@ben0x539 Better to do away with methods entirely and embrace the ML module? :-P
@ben0x539 Of course, he makes the point that free functions that accept your type can be part of its intf, but more awkward to abstract?
@ben0x539 also APIs are defined via traits/interfaces as a type with methods attached. Again OCaml's modules show another way.
@ben0x539 it's why I like the |> operator in OCaml and F#, you can use functions but still read left-to-right.
@ben0x539 and making it a method often aids discoverability, but that's a questionable benefit.
@ben0x539 I guess using methods means that you can read the data flow left-to-right esp when chained.
@ben0x539 have you seen this? http://t.co/Mqr0HViVi2
@ben0x539 Which language? What about, method if it needs "private" access or ad hoc polymorphism, function otherwise?
